An unprecedented future
JERUSALEM – With my now almost 90 years of life, I cannot recall a time when the past was so insignificant for political decision-making.
None of the significant developments of the present were predicted by anyone.
Experts examined the past, but due to their entrapment in old paradigms, they were unable to derive the future from it.
Due to the dynamic complexity of today's world, in which, given a scientifically grounded and rapidly changing global economy, even more events are interdependent, we are no longer able to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be shaped by scientific progress and innovation that cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and their leaders is diminishing. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome, because science and technology are borderless.
Global companies want to conduct their business worldwide, which on the one hand undermines sovereignty, but on the other hand weakens racism, prejudices, and significantly also nationalism.
As a result of this change, the fate of this world now lies in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically adept than their parents and connected to each other through social networks that transcend national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia mark not a clash of cultures, but a battle of generations.
The younger generation knows that the way states and economies are currently being led is unsuitable for the new times.
Yet there are political "free riders" who want to exploit this latest awakening. However, not by advancing an agenda of freedom, but by introducing new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, mainly Islamist extremists claim the protests of the younger generation for themselves, thereby stealing their revolution.
Israel has positively responded to the will of the young generation, but it can and should not interfere in the events of the Arab world.
We are with the rebellious youths at heart and their legitimate longing for freedom and fundamental rights that should enable them to be heard, to elect their political leaders, and to earn a living.
The Israelis are waiting for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, because existing as an island of prosperity amidst a sea of poverty is unnatural.
Yet there is a serious concern that politically well-organized extremists are trying to gain control over less well-organized liberals in elections, thereby preventing peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the region's fundamental problems.
The current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which also includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only basic reforms of established authority can pave the way toward freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example to others when it comes to achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, because its success is based on the fact that the country had absolutely nothing at the beginning.
Upon our return home, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could only rely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. As a result, today we have the highest per capita percentage of scientists and patents.
Approximately 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We use less water and yet achieve higher crop yields per square meter of cultivated area than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can also accomplish.
We are happy to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Above all, we must do everything in our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule over another people, and that is not Israel's destiny either.
We are sincerely interested in the creation of a Palestinian state that exists peacefully and side by side with Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, because resolving the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing extremists who aim to manipulate civil movements in order to advance their radical agenda.
The international community can support these efforts by providing incentives to those countries that strive for freedom and progress.
At the same time, decisive and groundbreaking political measures against extremists must be taken.
In particular, Iran is a source of moral decay, where extremism is furthered and reforms are blocked. Legitimate protests by its own citizens are crushed, and efforts are made against the courageous Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
Furthermore, Iran uses several proxies to incite terrorism against moderate forces within the Palestinian Authority, in Lebanon, and Iraq.
If Iran succeeds in acquiring nuclear weapons, the country's leaders could shake the Near and Middle East and further fuel extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
But not only Israel is threatened. Iran is a danger to peace and stability throughout the world.
The democracies of this world have declared that they will not allow Iran to acquire nuclear weapons. It is their duty to uphold this commitment before it becomes too late.
Beyond these short-term challenges, we all have the responsibility to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children to deal with the world of today.
At a time when the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education must offer all children the opportunity to realize their potential.
Today's teachers should motivate our children to be creative and innovative.
Self-realization is just as important as free expression of opinion.
I am writing this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overestimated and often restricts the courage needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back makes no sense.
